In article <28hgul$sdu@nic.umass.edu>, quilty@twain.ucs.umass.edu (Lulu of the lotus-eaters) writes:
|> Bennett Todd @ Salomon Brothers Inc., NY (bet@sbi.com) wrote:
|> : In article <28cghp$8em@cville-srv.wam.umd.edu>rsrodger@wam.umd.edu(.) writes:
|> : >	Question:  Instead of all of these complex password restrictions,
|> : >	wouldn't it be easier to offer the alternative of a really, really
|> : >	long password?
|> 
|> : Sure, passphrases are better. They require modifying every program that
|> : authenticates against /etc/passwd strings, where password choice
|> : restrictions can be put in place by just replacing _one_ program.
|> 
|> I'll admit to being somewhat of a Unix newbie, so I might be missing
|> something, but I don't get why using longer passphrases would require
|> changing more than the passwd program.  It seems to me (and many
|> people have mentioned this), that all you need do is use a good hash
|> to shorten the long passphrase down to the 8-bytes or whatever the old
|> password uses, then encrypt the hash by the normal means.

You would have to change the routines that the passwd program uses which
are in the libraries.  So unless your system has dynamic libraries and
all your programs are dynamically linked (not just passwd but login,
telnetd, rlogind etc.) you would need to recompile all of these as well.

